title: EBNF - Block Rules

Block rules are parser rules that match at //line-start positions//. Unlike inline rules, which match within a line of text, block rules consume one or more complete lines. Block content typically terminates at a double newline (blank line) or a matching closing marker. Many block rules -- such as lists, quote blocks, and tables -- can contain inline runs within them, meaning inline formatting like bold, italic, and links is parsed inside those blocks.

! Heading

A heading is one to six `!` characters at the start of a line, followed by optional CSS classes, optional whitespace, and then the heading text. The number of `!` characters determines the heading level (`<h1>` through `<h6>`).

```
Heading         ::= "!" { "!" } [ Classes ] [ Whitespace ] InlineRun Newline
                  (* 1 to 6 "!" characters *)
Classes         ::= { "." ClassName }
```

The heading text is parsed as an inline run, so it can contain bold, italic, links, and other inline formatting.

''Examples:''

```
! Heading level 1
!! Heading level 2
!!! Heading level 3
!.myclass Heading with a CSS class
!!.important.highlight Heading with two classes
```

! Horizontal Rule

A horizontal rule is three or more `-` characters on a line by themselves. It produces an `<hr>` element.

```
HorizRule       ::= "-" "-" "-" { "-" } Newline
                  (* 3 or more dashes *)
```

''Examples:''

```
---
-----
```

! List

A list is a sequence of lines, each starting with one or more list-marker characters. The marker characters determine the list type:

* `*` -- unordered list (`<ul>` / `<li>`)
* `#` -- ordered list (`<ol>` / `<li>`)
* `;` -- definition term (`<dl>` / `<dt>`)
* `:` -- definition description (`<dl>` / `<dd>`)
* `>` -- blockquote (`<blockquote>` / `<div>`)

Nesting is achieved by repeating marker characters. Markers can be mixed to create complex nested structures. Each list item's text is parsed as an inline run.

```
List            ::= ListItem { ListItem }
ListItem        ::= ListMarker [ Classes ] [ Whitespace ] InlineRun Newline
ListMarker      ::= MarkerChar { MarkerChar }
MarkerChar      ::= "*" | "#" | ";" | ":" | ">"
Classes         ::= { "." ClassName }
```

A list continues as long as consecutive lines begin with marker characters whose top-level type matches the first line. A blank line or a line that does not start with a marker ends the list.

''Examples:''

```
* Bullet item one
* Bullet item two
** Nested bullet item

# Numbered item one
# Numbered item two
## Sub-item

; Term
: Definition

> Blockquote line one
> Blockquote line two

*.myclass Bullet item with a CSS class

#** Mixed nesting: ordered > unordered > unordered
```

! Code Block

A fenced code block begins with three backticks and an optional language identifier, followed by a newline. It ends with three backticks on a line by themselves. The content inside is not wikified -- it is rendered as literal preformatted text.

```
CodeBlock       ::= "```" [ Language ] Newline
                  { CodeLine }
                  Newline "```"
Language        ::= WordChar { WordChar | "-" }
                  (* e.g., javascript, text/html, css *)
```

The language identifier must consist of word characters (`[a-zA-Z0-9_]`) and hyphens. If no language is provided, the code block is treated as plain text.

''Examples:''

<!-- The indentation prevents the parser from treating the backticks as real code fences -->

```
 ```
 Plain code block
 ```

 ```javascript
 var x = 42;
 ```

 ```css
 .myclass { color: red; }
 ```
```

! Quote Block

A quote block is delimited by `<<<` (three or more `<` characters). The opening line can include optional CSS classes and an optional opening cite (displayed above the quoted content). The closing `<<<` line can also carry a cite (displayed below the quoted content). The number of `<` characters in the closing marker must match the opening.

```
QuoteBlock      ::= OpenQuote [ Classes ] [ Whitespace ] [ InlineRun ] Newline
                  BlockContent
                  CloseQuote [ Whitespace ] [ InlineRun ] Newline
OpenQuote       ::= "<<<" { "<" }
CloseQuote      ::= "<<<" { "<" }  (* must match OpenQuote length *)
Classes         ::= { "." ClassName }
```

The block content between the markers is parsed as full block-level wikitext, so it can contain paragraphs, lists, headings, and other block rules.

''Examples:''

```
<<<
A simple quote block.
<<<

<<<.myclass An opening cite
Quoted text here.
<<<A closing cite

<<<<
Nested-style quote with four angle brackets.
<<<<
```

! Style Block

A style block wraps content in CSS styles and/or classes. It starts with `@@` followed by optional inline styles (as `property:value;` pairs) and/or CSS classes (as `.className`), then a newline. It closes with `@@` on a line by itself. Multiple opening lines of styles/classes can be stacked.

```
StyleBlock      ::= StyleOpener { StyleOpener }
                  BlockContent
                  "@@" Newline
StyleOpener     ::= "@@" [ Styles ] [ ClassList ] Newline
Styles          ::= StyleDecl { StyleDecl }
StyleDecl       ::= PropertyName ":" Value ";"
ClassList       ::= "." ClassName { "." ClassName }
```

Styles must precede classes on the same line. The block content is parsed as full block-level wikitext. Styles and classes are applied to each top-level element inside the block.

''Examples:''

```
@@.myClass
This paragraph gets the class "myClass".
@@

@@background-color:red;color:white;
Styled paragraph.
@@

@@width:100px;.myClass.otherClass
Styled paragraph with classes.
@@

@@.firstClass
@@font-size:1.5em;.secondClass
Multiple openers are combined.
@@
```

! Table

A table is a sequence of rows. Each row starts and ends with `|`. Cells are separated by `|`. A row can carry a suffix character after the final `|` to indicate its role.

Row suffixes:

* `h` -- header row (placed in `<thead>`)
* `f` -- footer row (placed in `<tfoot>`)
* `c` -- caption row (placed in `<caption>`)
* `k` -- class row (the cell content becomes a CSS class on the `<table>`)
* (none) -- body row (placed in `<tbody>`)

Special cell contents:

* `!` as the first character makes the cell a header cell (`<th>` instead of `<td>`)
* `~` merges the cell with the one above (rowspan)
* `>` merges the cell with the one to the right (colspan)
* `<` merges the cell with the one to the left (colspan)

Cell alignment is determined by leading/trailing spaces: a leading space means right-aligned, a trailing space means left-aligned, both means centered.

Vertical alignment: `^` at the start of cell content means top-aligned, `,` means bottom-aligned.

```
Table           ::= TableRow { TableRow }
TableRow        ::= "|" Cell { "|" Cell } "|" [ RowSuffix ] Newline
Cell            ::= [ CellAlign ] [ "!" ] InlineRun
                | "~"      (* rowspan *)
                | ">"      (* colspan right *)
                | "<"      (* colspan left *)
CellAlign       ::= [ "^" | "," ] { " " }
RowSuffix       ::= "h" | "f" | "c" | "k"
```

Cell content is parsed as an inline run, so it can contain links, bold, italic, and other inline formatting.

''Examples:''

```
|!Header 1|!Header 2|!Header 3|h
|Cell A1|Cell A2|Cell A3|
|Cell B1|Cell B2|Cell B3|
|Footer 1|Footer 2|Footer 3|f
|This is a caption|c
|myTableClass anotherClass|k

|>|Spans two columns|  <- colspan
|~|Spans two rows|  <- rowspan in second pass

| Right aligned |Left aligned| Centered |
|^Top aligned|,Bottom aligned|Normal|
```

! Typed Block

A typed block passes its content through a specified parser (identified by MIME type or file extension). Optionally, a render type can be specified to further transform the output. It opens with `$$$` and closes with `$$$` on a line by itself.

```
TypedBlock      ::= "$$$" [ ParseType ] [ " > " RenderType ] Newline
                  RawContent
                  Newline "$$$"
ParseType       ::= MimeType | FileExtension
                  (* e.g., text/html, .js, .svg, application/json *)
RenderType      ::= MimeType
                  (* e.g., text/html, text/plain *)
```

When no render type is given, the parsed content is inserted directly into the parse tree. When a render type is specified, the content is rendered to that type and wrapped in a `<pre>` element.

''Examples:''

```
$$$.js
var x = 42;
console.log(x);
$$$

$$$.svg
<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="100" height="100">
  <circle cx="50" cy="50" r="40" fill="blue" />
</svg>
$$$

$$$text/vnd.tiddlywiki>text/html
This will be rendered as an //HTML representation// of WikiText.
$$$
```

! Comment Block

An HTML comment block uses the standard `<!-- ... -->` syntax. Everything between the opening `<!--` and closing `-->` markers is ignored during rendering. Comment blocks can also appear in pragma position (before the body of a tiddler).

```
CommentBlock    ::= "<!--" CommentText "-->"
CommentText     ::= { AnyChar }   (* must not contain "-->" *)
```

CommentText must not contain the sequence `-->`.

''Examples:''

```
<!-- This is a comment and will not be rendered -->

<!--
Multi-line comment.
Also not rendered.
-->
```

! Conditional Block

The conditional block provides `if` / `elseif` / `else` branching based on filter expressions. If the filter produces any output, the condition is true. A double newline after `%>` causes the body to be parsed in block mode; otherwise it is parsed as an inline run.

The conditional rule is both a block and an inline rule -- it can appear at the start of a line or within flowing text.

```
Conditional     ::= IfClause { ElseIfClause } [ ElseClause ] EndIf
IfClause        ::= "<%if" Whitespace FilterExpr "%>" Body
ElseIfClause    ::= "<%elseif" Whitespace FilterExpr "%>" Body
ElseClause      ::= "<%else%>" Body
EndIf           ::= "<%endif%>"
FilterExpr      ::= (* a TiddlyWiki filter expression *)
Body            ::= InlineRun | BlockContent  (* block mode if preceded by blank line *)
```

''Examples:''

```
<%if [<myVar>match[yes]]%>
This is shown when myVar is "yes".
<%elseif [<myVar>match[maybe]]%>
This is shown when myVar is "maybe".
<%else%>
This is the fallback.
<%endif%>
```

Block mode (double newline after `%>`):

```
<%if [tag[important]]%>

! Important Content

This section is parsed as block-level wikitext.

<%endif%>
```

! Hard Line Breaks

The hard line breaks rule is actually an //inline// rule, but it is commonly grouped with block-level constructs because it controls line-level formatting. It is delimited by `"""` markers. Within this region, every newline is converted to a `<br>` element, preserving line breaks exactly as written.

```
HardLineBreaks  ::= '"""' [ Newline ]
                  { InlineRun Newline }
                  '"""'
```

Inline formatting is still parsed within the hard line breaks region.

''Examples:''

```
"""
This is line one
This is line two
This is line three
"""
```

Each line break in the source becomes an explicit `<br>` in the rendered output.

! Combined EBNF

The following grammar combines all block rules into a single reference.

```
(* ===== Block Rules ===== *)

BlockRule       ::= Heading
                | HorizRule
                | List
                | CodeBlock
                | QuoteBlock
                | StyleBlock
                | Table
                | TypedBlock
                | CommentBlock
                | Conditional
                | HardLineBreaks

(* --- Heading --- *)
Heading         ::= "!" { "!" } [ Classes ] [ Whitespace ] InlineRun Newline

(* --- Horizontal Rule --- *)
HorizRule       ::= "-" "-" "-" { "-" } Newline

(* --- List --- *)
List            ::= ListItem { ListItem }
ListItem        ::= ListMarker [ Classes ] [ Whitespace ] InlineRun Newline
ListMarker      ::= MarkerChar { MarkerChar }
MarkerChar      ::= "*" | "#" | ";" | ":" | ">"

(* --- Code Block --- *)
CodeBlock       ::= "```" [ Language ] Newline
                  { CodeLine }
                  Newline "```"
Language        ::= WordChar { WordChar | "-" }

(* --- Quote Block --- *)
QuoteBlock      ::= OpenQuote [ Classes ] [ Whitespace ] [ InlineRun ] Newline
                  BlockContent
                  CloseQuote [ Whitespace ] [ InlineRun ] Newline
OpenQuote       ::= "<<<" { "<" }
CloseQuote      ::= "<<<" { "<" }

(* --- Style Block --- *)
StyleBlock      ::= StyleOpener { StyleOpener }
                  BlockContent
                  "@@" Newline
StyleOpener     ::= "@@" [ Styles ] [ ClassList ] Newline
Styles          ::= StyleDecl { StyleDecl }
StyleDecl       ::= PropertyName ":" Value ";"
ClassList       ::= "." ClassName { "." ClassName }

(* --- Table --- *)
Table           ::= TableRow { TableRow }
TableRow        ::= "|" Cell { "|" Cell } "|" [ RowSuffix ] Newline
Cell            ::= [ CellAlign ] [ "!" ] InlineRun
                | "~"
                | ">"
                | "<"
CellAlign       ::= [ "^" | "," ] { " " }
RowSuffix       ::= "h" | "f" | "c" | "k"

(* --- Typed Block --- *)
TypedBlock      ::= "$$$" [ ParseType ] [ " > " RenderType ] Newline
                  RawContent
                  Newline "$$$"
ParseType       ::= MimeType | FileExtension
RenderType      ::= MimeType

(* --- Comment Block --- *)
CommentBlock    ::= "<!--" CommentText "-->"
CommentText     ::= { AnyChar }   (* must not contain "-->" *)

(* --- Conditional Block --- *)
Conditional     ::= IfClause { ElseIfClause } [ ElseClause ] EndIf
IfClause        ::= "<%if" Whitespace FilterExpr "%>" Body
ElseIfClause    ::= "<%elseif" Whitespace FilterExpr "%>" Body
ElseClause      ::= "<%else%>" Body
EndIf           ::= "<%endif%>"
Body            ::= InlineRun | BlockContent

(* --- Hard Line Breaks (inline rule) --- *)
HardLineBreaks  ::= '"""' [ Newline ]
                  { InlineRun Newline }
                  '"""'

(* ===== Shared Productions ===== *)
Classes         ::= { "." ClassName }
ClassName       ::= Letter { Letter | Digit | "-" | "_" }
InlineRun       ::= (* inline wikitext parsed until line end or terminator *)
BlockContent    ::= (* block-level wikitext parsed until closing marker *)
FilterExpr      ::= (* a TiddlyWiki filter expression *)
Whitespace      ::= " " { " " }
Newline         ::= [ CR ] LF
WordChar        ::= Letter | Digit | "_"
```
